{"key":"processedPost-16384134","value":{"id":16384134,"first":16383937,"last":16389452,"when":1339761076,"utime":"06/15/12 02:51 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>YouNeedMT said:</strong><br />Doesn't have a thermostat but it does have a timer that can be set to either off or on at a specific time, so i'll run it for a few hours in the night and before I go to bed to make sure the temps don't get too low.</blockquote><br />That's the opposite of what you want.&nbsp; A day/night temperature differential is beneficial.&nbsp; Run the heater during the day to warm up the air around the terrarium, and don't worry about it dropping at night.&nbsp; Place the terrarium near a bright window during the day to get some solar heating and you may not even need the heater.&nbsp; <br />I'd skip the idea of a hot rag under it.&nbsp; The <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">shotgun terrarium</a> works by having cooler air under and warmer air in the terrarium itself, caused by the lights and cakes or other substrates which provide heat.&nbsp; Since warm air is less dense than cool air, the cool air from below comes up into the terrarium, scrubbing moisture from the perlite to humidify the air above.&nbsp; Placing a heat source under the terrarium defeats the purpose.<br />RR","title":"Re: Novel idea for keeping a SGFC warm"}}